<div class="xar-mod-head">
  <span class="xar-mod-title"><xar:mlstring>Headlines Administration</xar:mlstring></span>
</div>
<div class="xar-mod-body">
  <xar:template type="module" file="admin-menu" />
  <img src="#xarTplGetImage('admin_generic.gif', 'base')#" alt="official icon" width="96" height="96" class="xar-module-icon" />
  <h2>
    <xar:mlstring>Overview</xar:mlstring>
  </h2>
  <h3>
    <xar:mlstring>What is it?</xar:mlstring>
  </h3>
  <p>
      <xar:mlstring>The Headlines module allows you to syndicate content from other website.  It also allows you to use predetermined hooks from Xaraya if you have them installed and activated.</xar:mlstring>
  </p>
  <h3>
    <xar:mlstring>How to use it?</xar:mlstring>
  </h3>
  <p>
      <xar:mlstring>You can use the headlines module in two main ways.</xar:mlstring>
      <ol>
          <li><xar:mlstring>Enter the URL to one or more feeds in the administration area, and allow 
              your users to browse those headlines from the main Headline user menu option.
              </xar:mlstring>
          </li>
          <li><xar:mlstring>In addition to the above user browsing throught the main Headlines user page,
              you can selectively import headline articles into one of your Article publication types. 
              This can be done in a batch, or by browsing and selecting which headline item to import. 
              </xar:mlstring>
          </li>
      </ol>
  </p>
  <h4>
    <xar:mlstring>Adding Feeds and Configuration</xar:mlstring>
  </h4>
  <p>
            <xar:mlstring>
            From the menu, you have three choices:
            </xar:mlstring>
            <ol>
                <li><xar:mlstring><strong>Add Headlines</strong>: Add a new syndication headline for processing.</xar:mlstring></li>
                <li><xar:mlstring><strong>Manage Headlines</strong>: View, edit and delete headlines that you have added to your site.
                        Add alternative titles and headlines for your feeds, and order the display of the feeds
                    </xar:mlstring>
                </li>
                <li><xar:mlstring><strong>Modify Configuration</strong>: Update the global configuration for the module.
                         Here you can set </xar:mlstring>
                         <ul>
                           <li><xar:mlstring>the number of feeds per page.</xar:mlstring></li>
                           <li><xar:mlstring>optionally select an Article module publication type to import the feed items. You will need a title and summary field in your publication type to import feed items (see Preparing Your Pubtype for Headline Import below).</xar:mlstring></li>
                           <li><xar:mlstring>choose which content to import to your selected publication type. Feed, Title, Description and an optional link to the originating feed item can also be added in your publication type summary field.
                              </xar:mlstring></li>
                           </ul>
                </li>
             </ol>

       </p>
  <h4>
    <xar:mlstring>Preparing Your Article Pubtype for Headline Import</xar:mlstring>
  </h4>
  <p>
      <xar:mlstring>The default News publication type in Articles, or similar is ideal for use with the Headlines module.
      The following fields and field types should be setup in your News publication type, or whichever is to be used for your Headlines. 
      Fields in your publication type such as status and pubdate are used in their usual function in the publication type, but not in the headline import process.
      </xar:mlstring>
  </p>
      <ol>
          <li><xar:mlstring><strong>Title</strong>: textbox - used to hold the imported headline title and link to the original feed item and source.</xar:mlstring></li>
          <li><xar:mlstring><strong>Summary</strong>: textarea - used to hold the imported summary of the headline item.</xar:mlstring></li>
          <li><xar:mlstring><strong>Body</strong>: textbox or URL property - used to hold the imported URL of the imported headline item.
              You will need to custom format this field as required for display in your pubtype display and summary template.</xar:mlstring></li>
          <li><xar:mlstring><strong>Notes</strong>: URL/Title property. By changing this to a URL/Title property it will automatically display the feed source and feed title as a
              clickable link on display of your imported headline item. However, you can format this as you need in your template. The content is imported and stored as a serialized array containing
              the URL of the feedsource and the title of your headline feed source (not the headline item).
          </xar:mlstring></li>
      </ol>
      <p><xar:mlstring>Future enhancements of this module may include mapping of pubtype fields to imported headline field.</xar:mlstring></p>
<h4>
    <xar:mlstring>Extending the display of Headlines</xar:mlstring>
  </h4>
        <p>
            <xar:mlstring>
            Hook the Categories module to Headlines to classify your feeds by category on display.
            </xar:mlstring>
        </p>
  <h3>
    <xar:mlstring>Included Blocks</xar:mlstring>
  </h3>
  <p>
            <ul>
                <li><xar:mlstring><strong>RSS Block</strong> allows you to provide selected feeds in blocks on your siten and define number of items, title, and refresh times.</xar:mlstring></li>
                <li><xar:mlstring><strong>Cloud Block</strong> Creates a cloud block from blog feeds, using Ping module to notify of updates and Scheduler module to update.</xar:mlstring></li>

            </ul>
       </p>
  <h3>
    <xar:mlstring>Included Hooks</xar:mlstring>
  </h3>
  <p>
            <xar:mlstring>There are no included hooks with Headlines</xar:mlstring>
  </p>
        <h3>
            <xar:mlstring>Credits</xar:mlstring>
        </h3>
      <p>
            <xar:mlstring>The RSS Block is using </xar:mlstring><a href="http://freshmeat.net/projects/phpfeedparser/?topic_id=914"> <xar:mlstring> PHP feedParser </xar:mlstring> </a><xar:mlstring> as its backend.   The notes for the feedParser by Reverend Jim are as follows</xar:mlstring>:
    </p>
    <p>
            <xar:mlstring>
            feedParser was created due to the lack of a good, flexible, class-based RSS feed parser for PHP. It has been built as a class, and currently handles RSS 0.91, RSS 0.92, RSS 0.93, RSS 1.0, and RSS 2.0 feeds. For channels it grabs the title, description, link, and creator. For items it grabs the title, description, link, and date. It also provides a form of the date converted into the local timezone to facilitate cronological sorting of items. The dates are provided in UNIX timestamp format for easy manipulation by other PHP functions. </xar:mlstring>
    </p>
        <h3><xar:mlstring>Further Information</xar:mlstring></h3>
  <p>
       <xar:mlstring>Extended information about this module can be found at </xar:mlstring><a title="#xarML('Headlines Module - Xaraya Extension 777')#" href="http://www.xaraya.com/index.php/release/777.html">Xaraya Extension and Releases</a>.
       </p>
      <ul>
          <li><xar:mlstring> Click on Version History tab at the bottom to get the latest release information.</xar:mlstring>
          </li>
          <li><xar:mlstring>Related tutorials and documentation on Headlines found at</xar:mlstring> <a href="http://www.xaraya.com/index.php/keywords/headlines/" title="#xarML('Related documentation on Headlines')#"><xar:mlstring>Xaraya Documentation.</xar:mlstring></a>
          </li>
      </ul>
